>Can anyone tell a layman what the hell happened to comics?
It all goes back to a deep impact event in comic books many decades ago. The Comics Code Authority was established by the government to moderate the subject matter of comic books, which at that point were deemed too sexual and violent. Before the code, you would be able to find and abundance of horror comics and romance comics, among other genres. All of which sold extremely well. But after the code, the only genre that survived was heavily censored capeshit. This caused the comic industry to shrink. By the 1980s, comics mostly existed in niche hobby shops, where before, they could be found in any given news stand or market. In order to make ends meet, comics had to increase their price tag. In the 90s, they resorted to gimmick sales like hologram covers. This inevitably failed and led to a complete industry crash. Certain jews were able to breathe new life into capeshit in the early 2000s. Hollywood bailed out a lot of their IPs. But the comics themselves still suffered. These days, comics delay the inevitable by hiring actual ESL spics to draw their capeshit for pennies, while they hire social justice college interns to write them.

Gates can receive or send. It's a one-way simplex protocol. Which has interesting consequences explored in some episodes of SG. Fuck, now that I think about it, it's a real graph theory computer science large-scale problem.

Anyways, the way to control it, from the point of view of the Earth stargate (really two of them, but the U.S got the master, Russia got the slave), is to schedule your simplex connection. That's a scheduled stargate access. "We" said, at 13h45s, that we will be accepting an incoming stargate simplex connection from somewhere precise in the galaxy. This connection will block all other stargate outgoing connections from this planet, not only use ours, and this will also block all stargate incoming connections, and possibly there are aliens that want to eat us behind, so you'd better believe we check on incoming connection.

Most SG teams only do scheduled offworld activations. We schedule them for a fucking reason. It's fucking important.

But sometimes, it's unscheduled. Unscheduled offworld activations can mean:

1. Aliens that want to eat us and just dialed in.
2. A lost SG teams that were in deep shit and want to go home now.

There is protocol for the 2., and actually plenty of checks in order to not kill any returning SG teams on the iris. But sometimes it's the 1.

SG-1, going into adventures, triggers 2. far too many times, it's weird they weren't routed into the Russian slave by pure accident.

>>178867407
They don’t understand the difference between absolute power as a concept and absolute monarchy as a system of governance. No one can functionally have true absolute power, but a system of government in which there is no constitution to limit the legal authority of the monarch is by definition an absolute monarchy. That doesn’t make the king a god and people can always act to impede the desires of a king or queen with sufficient support or cunning, but that doesn’t change the legal system. If you have to resort to extra-judicial tactics like assassination and war because you have no legal protections to limit the power of the monarch, then you live in an absolute monarchy. But I don’t honestly know why I’m taking the time to explain this because you already understand it and I’m pretty sure they’re just actively refusing to understand it out of sheer obstinate at this point. posts.com:
I will defend this movie so much because it tried something different in concept and action, unfortunately more basic movie making techniques it falls short in such as dialogue, story, acting etc. The "and my son line" was one of the worst lines I've heard.

Having rewatched it for the first time over christmas I wonder whether firstly Nolan could have done something to denote time travelling backwards, e.g. black and white or something maybe he avoided it because of Memento. It would definitely have made the action much easier to follow.

The marketing and core concept was probably off too. It wasn't a reversing time movie, it was reversing time with reversing physics. Stuff like the fire and explosions are too difficult to comprehend in the cinema, It's kind of like saying the alphabet backwards trying to figure out the reverse of an explosion.If they had of came up with a way much earlier in the movie to clearly explain some of these reverse physics concepts it might be easier to understand.

All that being said, I would consider this a more difficult movie to comprehend than primer. The concept of primer is simple, the only difficulty is in acknowledging that there's timelines not shown.

posts.com:
3 is the immediate drop in quality, losing Frank Darabont is such an noticeable catalyst for the decline.

S1 & 2 had different atmosphere, the show was about characters navigating an apocalyptic scenario and how their personalities clash. What made it interesting was how each POV was understandable. Dale and Glenn were diplomats, Shane pragmatic, Rick cautious, Andrea brazen.

Then in s3 this whole dynamic is changed so we have the governor, a villain with no motive or reason, a literal cartoonish psychopath.

A great example is how in s1 Rick struggles to gain the trust and authority over the group, even when his best friend and family are in it. In season 3 we’re supposed to believe the governor has climbed to the top of the Woodbury hierarchy while being a complete psychopath incapable of finishing a conversation without an outburst.

I guess that works for characters like Negan or the joker, but we usually see the mechanisms used to keep power (through fear - bar pool cue fight in dark knight, initial bank robbery, pitching generals against each other, public brandings etc). For the governor we get nothing. His motive and actions are whatever will satisfy the story direction, which is baffling because they then struggle to do anything interesting with the prison for most of the season. A total fucking shit show.

You are close to explaining what LOGH is all about.

Reinhard's society is one in which people's loyalty is to individual men, rather than roles, institutions or ideals.

The problem with this type of loyalty is illustrated by Ruenthal's rebellion. His troops loyalty was to him as an individual rather than the chain of command, and his loyalty to the Kaiser was loyalty to Reinhardt the man, not the office of Kaiser or the government around him.

Yang's attachment to democracy was a loyalty to institutions and ideals. That loyalty could be maintained even if bad men were in charge. A democracy enables bad leaders to be replaced by nonviolent means, whereas in Reinhardt's society, the only way for a regime change is violent conflict between charismatic leaders.

In a constitutional monarchy, loyalty is subtly shifted away from the man, to the role the man occupies. That helps mitigate the risk of violent conflict during an exchange of leadership.
